column2: almond butter and making six figures have in common? .

column1: they’re some of my favorite things and they all came together on this exact day one year ago. .
if you’re feeling stuck in life... keep reading ...
i was sitting on the kitchen floor in my underwear
column2: oprah ugly crying and eating almond butter out of the jar. (it's my favorite self care routine...oh like you haven't been there? 😜)

column1: i was in an industry i didn't recognize anymore. what i perceived to be a #metoo situation had me throwing up because of the stress. the doctors told me my right eye had hemorrhaged ... all because of the stress.
what's ironic? i was trying to make a health empowerment tv show (i know
column2: god's humor isn't lost on me either).

column1: but after one high level tv exec meeting after another...still nothing. so again...back to the almond butter and the crying.
i had failed a lot. in jobs. in relationships. i was feeling pretty low. .

and i was praying hard on my target kitchen rug in my target thong (i hate pants). and then i clearly heard god's voice. #bible i heard it clear as the san diego sky ... ""this year will be the year that changes you. everything will be pre and post this. you will make six figures. you will start your own path. you will become what you want to be a part of."" .

column2: quit the tv industry within the week. .
after two years of side hustling
column3: i actually invested in myself and went all in with building a company helping you become the best on camera.... and create videos and stories that tell the world how freaking awesome you are!!

column1: i got completely out of debt. made six figures. took my mom to italy. fell madly in love. worked remotely from europe. and i still refuse to wear pants.

column2: not because it's easy but because anything is possible. anything. one day this year i also woke up and my father had a brain tumor. this year i also lost my dear grandmother.

column1: life moves fast... you might as well do and be who and what you want

column1: 141017;instagram;2018-11-29 20:15:13;FALSE;"real talk: sexual assault 👉🏻recently i have talked with a lot of girls about sexual harassment. you know what is shocking? every. single. one had a story to tell. drunken guys dragging them into toilets
column2: asking a hundred times to have sex until the girl half heartedly gives in
column3: stalking and catcalling (which is not perceived as a compliment by girls). of course this happens to guys too
column4: but i’ve only talked to girls so far and i can only talk from my own experience. it can range from small things (guys checking you out in the gym because yes you are a girl lifting weights and suddenly they end up undressing themselves just training in shorts whilst looking at you in the mirror - yes happened) until the other end of the spectrum - your driver in indonesia locking the doors and trying to kiss you (yup) - to your driving teacher suddenly starting to massage you and play with your hair in the middle of a driving lesson. and the worst thing about it? girls feels guilty. at least i always did. i felt disgusting
column5: constantly asking myself if it has been my fault. if i had done something that could have left anybody thinking that i was somehow interested. but no. it’s not what you wear
column6: if you have makeup on or not
column7: if you smile to strangers on the street or if you train legs with a guy standing next to you. it is not you and it’s time that society starts blaming the ones who are to blame. have you ever experienced something alike? i’m curious to hear more about it. feel free to dm me if you’re not comfortable with leaving a comment ✨

column2: perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like “what did you do that made him beat you”. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.

“many of the women i’ve coached around dating + relationships (or who’ve read ‘the inner fix’ where we share a lot of sex-related stories that are very much in line with today’s #metoo movement) have opened up to me about some of their own sexual encounters which
column3: didn’t always feel entirely complicit (and in some cases

column2: most of these women hadn’t felt there was any point in telling anyone about such encounters because they were drunk at the time
column3: and so couldn’t remember all the details clearly - except for this one crucial fact: they are absolutely certain they’d said ‘no’ (or
column4: been asleep when it started – which is the same thing). the truth is
column5: since i started taking responsibility for my side of the street when it comes to my love + sex life
column6: i haven’t had any more of these ambiguous sexual encounters. maybe it’s because i’m no longer an easy target. maybe it’s because those sort of men aren’t drawn to me these days (or know i wouldn’t keep my mouth shut this time around).

column2: whilst i do think it’s imperative that both women and men take responsibility for how we’re showing up in the romantic + sexual arena (not least because it makes our lives a hundred times easier and more enjoyable)

column2: middle of the day and a man walking towards starts to mumble words to me... so i said ""excuse me?"" and he replied "" i said you look good
column3: it's a compliment! stick it up your fucking ass!"". i was so shocked to receive such a comment out of the blue. i felt violated
column4: as if had done something wrong... was worried about my clothes... was i too revealing? the angry response from this man i was instantly afraid and feared that his aggression would lead to attack (that i was too weak to handle!). i took this experience to my instagram story @zaranynette - i explained the situation and how angry i was that this sh*t keeps happening to me and i'm sick of it! i started asking for stories from other people who have had similar experiences. this blew up! i was contacted by around 90 women. no men spoke up to me about their experiences because i know men too get harassed and assaulted. so now i want to create a space to support others

column3: en vacances d’été avec mon père
column4: chez des amis à lui. il y avait aussi le fils du copain de mon père
column6: avec qui on était déjà partis l’année d'avant. il avait 2 ans de plus que moi
column7: était cool et vraiment beau gosse (#hipsterdes90s). bien évidemment je le kiffais. il était en pleine crise d’ado (#hormonesenfolie) et il matait et commentait chaque fille qui passait (#harcèlementderue). son père comme le mien ne disaient rien
column8: parfois un grognement et un “rhooo ça va on a compris
column9: tu la mets en sourdine”. parfois quand la fille était vraiment belle ils mataient aussi voire ricanaient à sa remarque. au fond de moi j’enviais ces filles qu’il regardait
column10: je voulais qu’il me regarde comme ça
column11: je voulais lui plaire et être aussi une “grande”. mais en y repensant je vois tout ce qui était merdique dans cette situation. le message c'était que c’est normal de juger les femmes sur leur physique et de les mater
column12: par contre tu le dis pas trop fort sauf si la meuf est vraiment bonne
column13: juste assez pour qu’on en profite aussi. aucun n'a dit “on ne parle pas comme cela de quelqu’un
column15: #jeunecondevientvieuxcon). le double effet kiss cool c’est qu'à cette époque je cherchais désespérément l’approbation de mon père. cela a ancré en moi pendant des années l'idée que le sexe était un moyen de plaire aux garçons et d’avoir leur attention et je vais en avoir la preuve le lendemain.

column1: pendant cette semaine de vacances donc
column2: le beau gosse en chaleur et moi dormions dans la même chambre dans chacun un lit simple
column3: à 1 mètre l’un de l’autre (#entrejeunes). comme tous les ados
column4: on passe la soirée à parler dans le noir. on a l’impression de refaire le monde. a un moment
column5: il me demande de coucher avec lui. je suis surprise: pour moi j’étais une gamine à ses yeux. je lui dit que je suis vierge
column6: il me répond qu’il n’a pas envie de me dépuceler “c’est relou” (#classe). par contre je peux “le branler ou le sucer” parce que “entre potes c’est normal
column7: ça se fait souvent”. je dis non
column8: je trouve ça dégueu. on continue de discuter.

column1: 141137;instagram;2018-11-29 22:30:51;FALSE;"lessons learned: women in difficult relationships: fight for your life and emerge a champion!
this may be the hardest lesson of all for me
column2: so i will start here. how do you fight for your life when you are broken and wounded to your soul?

column1: i have spent 10 years working on this book: to ensure i was healed
column2: to make sure i was doing this for the right reasons
column3: to make sure i was in place to handle what comes next
column4: to know that i have forgiven myself and all those who i needed to forgive.  i am on a mission.  to empower women to find the strength to tell their story...to unite us
column5: to help us heal and to forgive.  god has blessed me my whole life and led me to this scary place so that i can help others.

column1: i want to thank each and every one of you who have supported
column2: loved me and gotten me here!  thank you from the bottom of my heart.  you know who you are : )

column1: 141254;instagram;2018-11-30 01:41:44;FALSE;"as a feminist and supporter of humans sharing their stories
column2: i am realizing i have not shared my experience of sexual assault. i welcome you to not read further if you are not in a good space physically or mentally to do so.

column1: when i was 18 and living in toronto
column2: a neighbor in his late 30s invited me over to his apt to listen to music he produces. he locked both locks once we entered the apartment. he walked me through his living room and into his bedroom where the record player was. after 5 minutes of music and small talk
column3: he put porn on his tv and began rubbing my thighs. when i asked him to stop
column4: he wouldn’t. when i tried to get off the bed
column5: he pulled me back onto it and kissed me while forcefully massaging my crotch. when i tried to exit his bedroom
column6: he grabbed at my tear-away sweatpants and undid all he could. i pushed him off
column9: and ran. i was still a virgin and would be for another few months. when i told my first boyfriend about it
column10: he said “at least you weren’t raped...” so i stopped sharing my story. i guess i was suppose to feel lucky? as much as i’ve processed this over the last 11 years
column11: i know it still affects me. i check door locks always. i trust few with my body
column12: despite a sexually easy going demeanor. i hesitate to share my story because i feel like i wasn’t assaulted enough for it to “count”. i also worried that i wouldn't be physically strong enough to fight someone off if it happens again. then years later
column13: i was locked in an apartment by a partner who blocked my exits with his body and i fought. i grabbed a burner off the stove and held it to his throat and threw my first and only punch. i got out of those apartments and away from those men. i am so thankful for the voice of my sister @nmohler and my mother @debradubs leading me back to safety and self-love
column14: for the life of respect i share with my partner @lavenderbrvme
column15: to those who have shared their stories
column16: and for the work i have done to re-root myself in love
column18: and trust. i am proud of who i have made myself into.

column1: i remember many times over my life feeling as though i needed to hide myself or at least parts of my truth from others
column2: in order to feel safe. mostly because i felt afraid of their level of discomfort of my truth
column3: and how that discomfort would make me feel internally as a result. i coined the term: “what if”aholic- what if this person reacts this way
column4: what if i hurt their feelings
column6: what if they no longer value me
column8: what if they abandon me.... and the list goes on and on and on til the mother fricking break of dawn. today
column9: i am grateful to know that being seen is exactly what people are craving- authenticity is the antidote to disconnection from self and others. being brave enough to stand in one’s truth is the path to connection. wow
column10: who would have thought?! it wasn’t about fighting against the crimes
column11: it wasn’t about hiding the injustices
column12: it wasn’t ever about pretending to be something i wasn’t to appease others.... all this time (and the research shows this to be true)
column13: it was really about being myself. owning my flaws
column14: owning my secrets and recognizing that i am no less than or greater than anyone else. sharing my message today is possible because of the many women in my past that have fought for me to have equal rights to share my voice. to speak out about what it is that is in my heart to be true (right or wrong- the point is mute). i am grateful for the opportunity to have my freedom of speech
column15: to share my stories and my vulnerabilities today. i thank all the women who have fought tirelessly
column16: and continue to fight for my rights. i ask these same women
column17: to trust the process. trust in the fruits of your labor. allow our generation to demonstrate what it is that you’ve been fighting for. let us show you why you fought
column18: and allow us to experiment with our sense of connecting to the divine feminine and divine masculine. it is in my truth that i must stand strong
column19: just as you have stood tall before me. and

141343;instagram;2018-11-30 04:29:38;FALSE;do you believe in the law of attraction? .
to keep it simple- what you think
by being aware of your thoughts you can take better care of your life and those around you! .

try to release any doubts or negativity and convert them into positivity! instead of thinking “i really don’t want to fail. i’m not good enough.” accept that you might be feeling a little nervous about whatever it is you are going for (because it’s human nature to feel!)..... take a deep breathe and just relax. clear your mind and practice transforming that previous thought into the opposite - a positive statement saying- “i’m going to do the best i can and will succeed! i am always good enough” ..... because you are. .
if you think 3 positive thoughts before you go to bed and repeat them as a mantra- you will wake up feeling more refreshed
column3: and ready to take on the day! hope this has been helpful to someone and that everyone has a blessed friday!✨💜✨💜✨💜✨💜 .

column1: 141344;instagram;2018-11-30 04:29:38;FALSE;"wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014
column2: when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

column1: documents show the john bolton super pac
column2: which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton
column4: 700 in 2014 for ""behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging."" those services included strategies that broke individual voters into ""clusters"" based on what messages would resonate with them.

column1: wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign
column2: such as ""drain the swamp"" and imagery of walls. ""a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014

column1: he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. ""everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval
column3: who left the company in late 2014.

column1: 141349;instagram;2018-11-30 04:36:47;FALSE;"when i launched my open spaces collection about two months ago i wrote that the collection was inspired by “the myriad ways we move and use our bodies” and while that is true it’s not the whole truth. it was also inspired - very directly - by the #metoo movement and all of the beautiful energy it has created in the lives of women
column3: and anyone who identifies as a woman. i’ve been thrilled by the societal movements i’ve seen gain momentum in the last year or two. trans rights
column6: the general patriarchy we’re all living in is no longer the elephant in the room. this is not at all an all-inclusive list. but these and more are all things i struggled with and wished were more a part of the general dialogue of our society when i was in my teens. i grew up in a suburb not far from sf
column7: but in many ways it had much more in common with the middle parts of our country than it did the liberal bay. i constantly felt like an outsider. i constantly felt an undercurrent of dread - like if the folks around me knew how i felt i’d be in danger. during my late teens
column10: sometimes life didn’t feel safe. my current life looks very different
column11: but overall i feel much more comfortable to express myself
column12: and not fear for my safety. we’ve made so many great strides as a society
column13: and i hope we continue to make them. (and we of course have a long fucking way to go.) this is all to say this: all of this energy and more was poured into creating open spaces. i just wanted to share all of this with all of you tonight
column14: thinking this might resonate with some. if you want to see more
column15: click the link in my profile and select “open spaces.” and i don’t say this to try to sell you anything
column16: but rather to just share some energy and some thoughts. good night for now my loves! .

column5: and i am grateful everyday that i am given so many opportunities and encouragment.

column2: domestic abuse or relationship abuse) is a pattern of behaviors used by one partner to maintain power and control over another partner in an intimate relationship.

column1: domestic violence does not discriminate. anyone of any race
column4: religion or gender can be a victim – or perpetrator – of domestic violence. it can happen to people who are married
column5: living together or who are dating. it affects people of all socioeconomic backgrounds and education levels.

column1: domestic violence includes behaviors that physically harm
column3: prevent a partner from doing what they wish or force them to behave in ways they do not want. it includes the use of physical and sexual violence
column5: emotional abuse and economic deprivation. many of these different forms of domestic violence/abuse can be occurring at any one time within the same intimate relationship.

not all of these women are survivors of sexual violence
column2: but statistically 1 in 4 women will experience rape or sexual assault in her lifetime.

column1: this trailer features just some of the women’s stories you will find in our book ‘100 women i know’
column2: it’s not an easy read but a necessary one.

column1: our documentary film of the same title is screening at our event this thursday. the documentary is based on 100 responses to a questionnaire about rape and sexual assault. four young women sit in their bedrooms
column2: unapologetically telling their stories of rape. the intimate insight into these brave women’s experiences is powerful
column3: and thought provoking. from hearing these women’s stories
column4: and their reflections on their experiences
column5: ‘100 women i know’ encourages you to consider the (often unshared) stories of the women you know.

column1: this project aims to bring together and foster solidarity between everyone who has experienced sexual violence.

the film has been touring the film festival circuit internationally for the last 2 years. we want to continue to screen it - please get in touch if you can offer us a platform to do so. for anyone interested you can find upcoming listings on our website.
thank you to every person who has volunteered to work on this project wether affected or not
column2: when we stand together in solidarity powerful things happen.

column1: not all of these women are survivors of sexual violence
column2: but statistically 1 in 4 women will experience rape or sexual assault in her lifetime.

column1: this trailer features just some of the women’s stories you will find in our book ‘100 women i know’
column2: it’s not an easy read but a necessary one.

column1: our documentary film of the same title is screening at our event this thursday. the documentary is based on 100 responses to a questionnaire about rape and sexual assault. four young women sit in their bedrooms
column2: unapologetically telling their stories of rape. the intimate insight into these brave women’s experiences is powerful
column3: and thought provoking. from hearing these women’s stories
column4: and their reflections on their experiences
column5: ‘100 women i know’ encourages you to consider the (often unshared) stories of the women you know.

column1: this project aims to bring together and foster solidarity between everyone who has experienced sexual violence.

the film has been touring the film festival circuit internationally for the last 2 years. we want to continue to screen it - please get in touch if you can offer us a platform to do so. for anyone interested you can find upcoming listings on our website.
thank you to every person who has volunteered to work on this project wether affected or not

column1: 141391;instagram;2018-11-30 05:50:47;FALSE;"this has been a long time coming. 10 years ago i told corrina of aware that one day
column2: when i am ready i would come forward and reach out to other survivors. my first experience was when i was 13.

column1: after i said that to her
column3: i have survived more sexual violence ranging from stalking to molestation on public transport to sexual harassment at work and sexual assault.

column2: challenging journey of healing. there have been attempted suicides

column1: i wrote a paper in university as my own catharsis on violence against women and wrote for the school newspaper and contributed poems and articles on relates topics. i contributed articles to aware and also to the recently launched #aimforzero campaign.

column2: i curated a show “celebrating women” with 15 visual artists and performance artists including my dear friend @deborahemmanuel and a percentage of artwork sales proceeds went to aware.

column1: 2014-2015 i was part of a first video for aware’s launch of their sexual assault care centre #sacc where our voices were recorded and animations were put in place as we did not feel ready to be seen. i could not sleep for 3 days leading up to the recording and had nightmares and flashbacks of the various attacks and i dreamt they came to attack me again. i was shaking and crying before

i was so nervous about this whole week but at the same time excited and proud of myself for how far i have come. i celebrate my strength and truth. i am tired of hiding and being small. thank you for all the support and love the past week
the suffering of our society needs to end. let’s choose better as a #community #sexualviolence is everybody’s issue.
please watch the video of our survival and strength and pledge to end the violence against all beings:

column1: 141571;instagram;2018-11-30 11:49:32;FALSE;"dags att hylla en till av våra medlemsjourer
beskriv er jour med tre ord:
vad är ni mest stolta över med jouren ni är på:
flera saker 🙂. - att vi är sveriges första tjejjour. vi har över 20 års erfarenhet av att stötta och stärka tjejer! - att vi
column2: trots begränsade resurser och flera utmaningar
column3: stöttade över 2000 tjejer och unga kvinnor förra året och minst lika många 2018! - att vår ambition är att stå stadigt i vår feministiska analys. med det menar vi t.e.x att vi inte följer trender i samhällsdebatten eller jourrörelsen utan vågar gå vår egen väg och sticka ut hakan om det behövs och vi anser att gynnar våra stödsökande. - att vi alltid och på flera sätt backar våra stödsökande
column4: i stödverksamheten såväl som i offentliga och mediala sammanhang. - och sist men inte minst så är vi så oerhört tacksamma för och stolta över våra jourtjejer som verkligen brinner för stockholms tjejjour och våra stödsökande! de är ju de som är stockholms tjejjour!

column1: har ni någon hjärtefråga på jouren som ni har lite extra fokus på:

sedan en tid tillbaka kämpar vi med att lyfta bristen på traumabehandling för tjejer och unga kvinnor som utvecklat ptsd som en konsekvens av att de utsatts för sexuellt våld. detta är en oerhört viktig fråga som vi kommer fortsätta att arbeta med där vi innerligt hoppas på att vi kommer se en förändring. i dagsläget står skrämmande många utan den hjälp och det stöd till som de har rätt till. det finns inga specialistenheter eller mottagningar
column2: vilket vi vet är en nödvändighet när det kommer till trauma och det finns undermålig kunskap inom psykiatrin. vi började lyfta frågan i slutet av 2016 i samband med att socialförvaltningen förändrade mikamottagningens verksamhet
column3: att vi står och stampar här fortfarande

column1: beskriv er jour med tre ord:
vad är ni mest stolta över med jouren ni är på:
flera saker 🙂. - att vi är sveriges första tjejjour. vi har över 20 års erfarenhet av att stötta och stärka tjejer! - att vi
column2: trots begränsade resurser och flera utmaningar
column3: stöttade över 2000 tjejer och unga kvinnor förra året och minst lika många 2018! - att vår ambition är att stå stadigt i vår feministiska analys. med det menar vi t.e.x att vi inte följer trender i samhällsdebatten eller jourrörelsen utan vågar gå vår egen väg och sticka ut hakan om det behövs och vi anser att gynnar våra stödsökande. - att vi alltid och på flera sätt backar våra stödsökande
column4: i stödverksamheten såväl som i offentliga och mediala sammanhang. - och sist men inte minst så är vi så oerhört tacksamma för och stolta över våra jourtjejer som verkligen brinner för stockholms tjejjour och våra stödsökande! de är ju de som är stockholms tjejjour!

column1: har ni någon hjärtefråga på jouren som ni har lite extra fokus på:

sedan en tid tillbaka kämpar vi med att lyfta bristen på traumabehandling för tjejer och unga kvinnor som utvecklat ptsd som en konsekvens av att de utsatts för sexuellt våld. detta är en oerhört viktig fråga som vi kommer fortsätta att arbeta med där vi innerligt hoppas på att vi kommer se en förändring. i dagsläget står skrämmande många utan den hjälp och det stöd till som de har rätt till. det finns inga specialistenheter eller mottagningar

column1: 141666;instagram;2018-11-30 14:17:15;FALSE;"when the #metoo movement started i didn’t share my experiences.
i can write poems. they’re quick
column2: a little blood-letting to relieve the pressure
column3: whatever the feeling or idea may be.
i still haven’t tackled those. i agonize over essays. i’m tortured by long-form
column4: not that i don’t enjoy it
column5: but once i give myself the permission to move outside the confines of a poem—i can’t stop going. when i give myself space to think for these pieces though
column7: realize what actually qualifies (so much more than you’d think unfortunately
column8: and maybe qualifies isn’t the word)
column9: it’s almost sickening. it’s hard to do that work but i’m trying. i’ll finish writing those stories when i can.

column1: i’m a year late but it’s never too late. always in awe of women in general. this is a poem for y’all.

column1: मुझे अपनी तरफ कुछ इस तरह आकर्षित कर रहा है
जैसे इस जुस्तजू की दरकार मुझे सारी ज़िन्दगी रही हो
मेरे मन में उठे तूफानों को
लहरों ने जैसे नया जन्म दिया है
समुद्र की क्रांति जैसे मेरी ही क्रांति हो
सीमाओं को तोड़कर आज़ाद बहने की बेताब तमन्ना
एक ज़िद्दी दिल का अजीब सा पागलपन
जो मुझे सिर्फ विचलित समुद्र में मिला
संभवतः मेरी आत्मा का एक बड़ा हिस्सा
समुद्र के क्रोध से बना है
मेरी स्वाधीनता का अपमान किया है
मेरी आज़ादी का तिरस्कार करने का दुस्साहस किया है
जिस दिन मेरा क्रोध अपनी चरम सीमा पार कर लेगा
उस दिन यही वद्रोह एक क्रांति का रूप लेगा
जो सम्पूर्ण सृष्टि का विनाश करने की शक्ति रखती है
और तब तक इन उफनती बहती लहरों की तरह
मेरा क्रोध भी तुम्हें मौका देगा
मेरी आज़ादी जो तुमने सदियों से छीन रखी है
तोड़ने की कगार पर उतर आया

";[ एक और विद्रोह आज़ादी के लिए ] समुद्र का विद्रोह मुझे अपनी तरफ कुछ इस तरह आकर्षित कर रहा है जैसे इस जुस्तजू की दरकार मुझे सारी ज़िन्दगी रही हो मेरे मन में उठे तूफानों को इन तेज़ बढ़ती पत्थरों पर फूटती लहरों ने जैसे नया जन्म दिया है समुद्र की क्रांति जैसे मेरी ही क्रांति हो सीमाओं को तोड़कर आज़ाद बहने की बेताब तमन्ना एक ज़िद्दी दिल का अजीब सा पागलपन जो मुझे सिर्फ विचलित समुद्र में मिला संभवतः मेरी आत्मा का एक बड़ा हिस्सा समुद्र के क्रोध से बना है यह क्रोध विद्रोह है हर उस इंसान के ख़िलाफ़ जिसने प्रकृति के विरुद्ध जाकर मेरी स्वाधीनता का अपमान किया है मेरी आज़ादी का तिरस्कार करने का दुस्साहस किया है जिस दिन मेरा क्रोध अपनी चरम सीमा पार कर लेगा उस दिन यही वद्रोह एक क्रांति का रूप लेगा एक ऐसी क्रांति जो सम्पूर्ण सृष्टि का विनाश करने की शक्ति रखती है और तब तक इन उफनती बहती लहरों की तरह मेरा क्रोध भी तुम्हें मौका देगा मेरी आज़ादी जो तुमने सदियों से छीन रखी है उसे वापस लौटा देने का क्यूंकि जिस दिन मेरा क्रोध तुम्हारे ज़बरदस्ती के नियम कानून तोड़ने की कगार पर उतर आया उस दिन सिर्फ़ विनाश ही विनाश होगा -प्राची अग्रवाल picture credits : ajani_shaily ;[('['

बढ़ती पत्थरों पर फूटती लहरों ने जैसे नया जन्म दिया है समुद्र की क्रांति जैसे मेरी ही क्रांति हो सीमाओं को तोड़कर आज़ाद बहने की बेताब तमन्ना एक ज़िद्दी दिल का अजीब सा पागलपन जो मुझे सिर्फ विचलित समुद्र में मिला संभवतः मेरी आत्मा का एक बड़ा हिस्सा समुद्र के क्रोध से बना है यह क्रोध विद्रोह है हर उस इंसान के ख़िलाफ़ जिसने प्रकृति के विरुद्ध जाकर मेरी स्वाधीनता का अपमान किया है मेरी आज़ादी का तिरस्कार करने का दुस्साहस किया है जिस दिन मेरा क्रोध अपनी चरम सीमा पार कर लेगा उस दिन यही वद्रोह एक क्रांति का रूप लेगा एक ऐसी क्रांति जो सम्पूर्ण सृष्टि का विनाश करने की शक्ति रखती है और तब तक इन उफनती बहती column1: 141734;instagram;2018-11-30 15:46:04;FALSE;"i feel like when you start a new job and move cities all at the same time it can take a while to get on your feet. i haven't forgotten about one in five even if there's not being much posted - the last few months have been a lot behind the scenes
column2: there is so many diaries out as well as shoots planned in the new year. i started this project just over a year ago and in the last few months participants have tripled in numbers. i was and am sick of the way victims of sexual assault/rape get spoken about
column3: how society constantly disbelieve someone's truth
column4: how society are easy to believe someone would lie about being raped rather than believe someone could commit the crime. anyone who has read interviews or pieces i have written about one in five know that i created this project from my own diary as this was my coping method it was never intended to be shown
column5: it was my coping mechanism and outlet when people shut down my truth and told me that i had caused it. my voice was silenced for years but not now and even if i'm not constantly posting new extracts my voice is just as loud as it ever has been. if you would like to be part of the project please check faq in my highlights or get in touch. extract sixteen from #oneinfive you can read the text in the comments. .

brothel in #borneo - this 7 year old #orangutan named pony was used as a prostitute in #indonesia
column4: heavily made-up and forced to let men sexually abuse her.

column1: pony's captor was a woman. the madam held pony captive for many years. pony waited chained for her next 'client.' she was taught to gyrate her hips for them after which they’d rape her. the brothel had many human prostitutes but most of the clients specifically asked for pony so she was the chief source of the madam’s income.

the police tried to free pony on several occasions but the villagers threatened the police with guns. it took 35 armed policemen to free pony after which she was transferred to her new home - the borneo orangutan survival foundation.
she cannot be released into the wild as she has never learned how to survive. all she has ever known is cruelty
column2: abuse and human depravity. due to a lack of law enforcement in indonesia
column3: these people didn't face any sentence or punishment for what they had done.
